english:
  title: Preface to the Poetry Manuscript of Cheonbong
  author: Lee Sung-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Since I fell into exile, I have wandered as a man of no fixed place—east, west, south, and north alike. People have turned their backs and fled, warning one another not to draw near. Yet among the Buddhist monks, there were those who came to visit and those who wrote to inquire. At Seongsan I found Gyeongran, at Janghung I found Haknam and Seongsmin, at Seowon I found Sanghyeong, and near Jungwon I found Tunwu. These are all men who have cast aside the pursuit of fame and profit, who have fled into the realm of emptiness.

    When Tunwu had followed me in my travels for more than a month, one day he brought forth a collection of his poems and showed them to me. They are clear without becoming harsh, crude without becoming vulgar, rich without becoming excessive. The longer one reads them, the more one finds the weariness lifting. The world preserves the Collection of Nine Monks from the Tang dynasty, which I too have glimpsed in passing—yet could I willingly concede that Tunwu's achievement falls far short of theirs? And yet, the craft or crudeness of poetry is insufficient measure for judging Tunwu. For Tunwu bears toward me no bond of kinship, no ties of shared homeland, no debt of mutual aid in times of hardship, and yet he has stood by me through calamity without hesitation or reserve. What he has gained lies deeper than poetry itself. Should those who read Tunwu's verses in ages to come speak of him merely as "a poet-monk," they would not truly know him. Therefore I write this account of the man himself. Tunwu's dharma name is Cheonbong, and he is a foremost disciple of Hwanam.
  footnotes:
    - The Buddhist monks mentioned (Gyeongran, Haknam, Seongsmin, Sanghyeong, and Tunwu) were among the few who maintained friendship with Lee Sung-in during his exile, a sign of their spiritual detachment from worldly concerns.
    - The 'Collection of Nine Monks' (Guseung-jip) refers to an anthology of Tang dynasty Buddhist poetry, representing the highest standard of monastic verse tradition.
    - Cheonbong (Thousand Peaks) is the dharma name of Tunwu; Hwanam (Illusory Hermitage) was his teacher.
